{"ts":"2026-06-27T13:46:03.120Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Considering Backend Tests**\n\nI've got it! I'm now contemplating how to integrate backend tests. I've realized we've got a mock Next.js App Router API layer and a Python FastAPI backend using SQLite. The task directives are clear: lightweight smoke tests or a verification script, but hands-off for the landing page and GFF AI tools. I'm exploring whether pytest is usable.\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
{"ts":"2026-06-27T13:46:04.763Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Adding Pytest Tests**\n\nI'm now zeroing in on integrating pytest. It seems like the safest and simplest route for backend testing. I've decided on the scope: health checks, login/auth, RBAC route checks, client dashboard data verification, project listing tests, and support ticket creation testing. I am considering where to put them, probably `backend/app/tests/`, and if there's existing pytest config to leverage. I'm reviewing FastAPI backend routes to confirm they are testable.\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
{"ts":"2026-06-27T13:46:07.215Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Verifying Route Availability**\n\nI'm now deep-diving into the FastAPI backend's routes. The health and login routes are verified under `/api/v1/health` and `/api/v1/auth/login`. However, I've found there's no `/me` route for user details, requiring me to add one in `backend/app/api/routes/auth.py`. This new route will retrieve the current user, using the `get_current_user` dependency, and I have verified the `UserResponse` schema is available.\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
{"ts":"2026-06-27T13:46:08.785Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Analyzing Admin Route Access**\n\nOkay, I've confirmed an admin-only route exists: `/api/v1/clients`. I'm going to focus on an RBAC test for it, which will confirm non-admin users receive a 403 Forbidden error. This is perfect for verifying role-based access.\n\n\\n\\n\nI'm now determining what a dashboard route should provide, and if it should even be in the backend. I need to figure out what a dashboard route will return, and am investigating the existing models and routes. I'm focusing on adding routes for the project and support ticket functionality, to include them for testing.\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
